04153nam a22005415i 9780520939899DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209398997 a10.1525/97805209398992doi  a(DE-B1597)519603  a(OCoLC)773565070  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPS1322b.I7 2003eb 7aLIT0040202bisacsh1 aTwain, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIs He Dead? :bA Comedy in Three Acts /cMark Twain; Shelley Fisher Fishkin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (246 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJumping Frogs: Undiscovered, Rediscovered, and Celebrated Writings of Mark Twain ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tIs He Dead? by Mark Twain -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe University of California Press is delighted to announce the new publication of this three-act play by one of America's most important and well-loved writers. A highly entertaining comedy that has never appeared in print or on stage, Is He Dead? is finally available to the wide audience Mark Twain wished it to reach. Written in 1898 in Vienna as Twain emerged from one of the deepest depressions of his life, the play shows its author's superb gift for humor operating at its most energetic. The text of Is He Dead?, based on the manuscript in the Mark Twain Papers, appears here together with an illuminating essay by renowned Mark Twain scholar Shelley Fisher Fishkin and with Barry Moser's original woodcut illustrations in a volume that will surely become a treasured addition to the Mark Twain legacy. Richly intermingling elements of burlesque, farce, and social satire with a wry look at the world market in art, Is He Dead? centers on a group of poor artists in Barbizon, France, who stage the death of a friend to drive up the price of his paintings. In order to make this scheme succeed, the artists hatch some hilarious plots involving cross-dressing, a full-scale fake funeral, lovers' deceptions, and much more. Mark Twain was fascinated by the theater and made many attempts at playwriting, but this play is certainly his best. Is He Dead? may have been too "out there" for the Victorian 1890s, but today's readers will thoroughly enjoy Mark Twain's well-crafted dialogue, intriguing cast of characters, and above all, his characteristic ebullience and humor. In Shelley Fisher Fishkin's estimation, it is "a champagne cocktail of a play--not too dry, not too sweet, with just the right amount of bubbles and buzz."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArtistsxDrama. 0aDeathxDrama. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aFishkin, Shelley Fisher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520939899.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles